00:00:03.020 --> 00:00:04.950
This is a circle, you probably knew that.

00:00:04.950 --> 00:00:06.930
If we were to turn this circle on

00:00:06.930 --> 00:00:09.860
and watch it go up and
down and up and down

00:00:09.860 --> 00:00:11.680
and trace that motion out,

00:00:11.680 --> 00:00:13.680
you get what's called a
sine wave, which you know

00:00:13.680 --> 00:00:15.710
to be important in things
like pendulum motion,

00:00:15.710 --> 00:00:17.540
particle physics, things of that nature.

00:00:17.540 --> 00:00:20.050
Sine waves are important but for my money,

00:00:20.050 --> 00:00:22.390
the coolest thing about 'em
is you can add them together

00:00:22.390 --> 00:00:25.780
to do other things, which
sounds simple until you realize

00:00:25.780 --> 00:00:29.140
this is how the 2018 Nobel
Prize in physics was won.

00:00:29.140 --> 00:00:30.840
My buddy, Brady Haron,
has a really good video

00:00:30.840 --> 00:00:32.580
about that overall on Sixty Symbols.

00:00:32.580 --> 00:00:34.080
There's some fancy math I learned

00:00:34.080 --> 00:00:36.950
at the university called
the Fourier Series.

00:00:36.950 --> 00:00:39.610
These are my old notebooks
and check this out.

